Hi-C processing 101

Author

Jacques SERIZAY

Published

January 25, 2023

Aim: This workshop aims at learning from scratch how to process, check, visualize and integrate Hi-C data with other datasets.

More specifically, this will teach you:

  • Set up a conda environment and install the required packages with micromamba

  • Align fastq files to a genome reference and generate a .pairs file with hicstuff

  • Understand the sanity checks performed by hicstuff

  • Bin filtered pairs into a contact matrix (.cool) using cooler

  • Generate a balanced, multi-resolution contact matrix file (.mcool) with cooler

  • Identify features (e.g.Â loops) using chromosight

  • Use R to perform advanced operations on contact matrices:

    • Import and subset contact matrices (.cool, .hic, HiC-Pro derivedâ¦)
    • Import and subset pairs files
    • Arithmetics: merge, divide, smoothen, balance, autocorrelate, â¦
    • Analysis: P(s), virtual 4C, scalograms, cis/trans interactions
    • Mapping: chromatin loops (via chromosight), topological domains, compartments
    • Visualizing: contact maps, features, aggregated maps, saddle plots

  • Integrate other genome-wide modalities (RNA-seq, ChIP-seq, â¦)

conda vs anaconda vs miniconda vs mamba vs micromamba

All these softwares fit the same purpose: managing package installation in dedicated environments. conda is the actual package manager, while anaconda or miniconda are software distributions, i.e.Â a set of softwares, including conda. anaconda includes 150+ scientific softwares whereas microconda has a much tinier disk storage footprint. It includes python by default, but not much else. mamba and micromamba are a newer flavour of conda and miniconda: they can perform the same types of operations (create environment, install packages, â¦) but much faster as it supports parallelized jobs!

3.2 Running hicstuff

The generic command for hicstuff pipeline is something like:

## GENERIC COMMAND: TO COMPLETE
## DO NOT RUN THIS!
hicstuff pipeline \
   <some-options> \
   --genome genomes/S288c/S288c.fa \ # Genome info
   data/CH112_S4_R1_001.gz \ # read R1 info
   data/CH112_S4_R2_001.gz   # read R2 info
Options I find useful
  • âdistance-law Generates a distance law file and plot
  • âduplicates Filter out PCR duplicates based on read positions.
  • âenzyme={STR|INT} Restriction enzyme or âmnaseâ
  • âfilter Filter out spurious 3C events (loops and uncuts) using hicstuff filter (Cournac et al.Â BMC Genomics, 2012)
  • âmapping=STR normal|iterative|cutsite mapping strategy
  • âmatfmt=STR The format of the output sparse matrix. Can be âbg2â for 2D Bedgraph format, âcoolâ for Mirnylabâs cooler software, or âgraalâ for graal-compatible plain text COO format. [default: graal]
  • âno-cleanup Super important!! Needed to keep intermediate pairs file
  • âoutdir=DIR Output directory
  • âplot Generates informative QC plots in the output directory at different steps of the pipeline.
  • âprefix=STR Overrides default filenames and prefixes all output files with a custom name.
  • âthreads=INT Number of threads to allocate.

So, for me, a typical âextendedâ hicstuff pipeline command may look like this:

bash
hicstuff pipeline \
   --distance-law \
   --duplicates \
   --enzyme DpnII,HinfI \
   --filter \
   --mapping normal \
   --matfmt cool \
   --no-cleanup \
   --outdir results \
   --plot \
   --prefix CH112 \
   --threads 12 \
   --genome genomes/S288c/S288c.fa \
   data/CH112_S4_R1_001.gz \
   data/CH112_S4_R2_001.gz

4 Few notes on hicstuff pipeline

  • IMO, --filter is what makes hicstuff unique compared to other workflows. DO USE IT!!
  • --matfmt cool should be default in hicstuff. IMO, other formats are not as convenient, especially if you are going to map on larger genomes.
  • With longer reads, I would typically run hicstuff in --mapping iterative mode to map as many reads as possible.
  • If you are looking for maximum mappability and pairs number, --mapping cutsite will further increase these numbers. It will also exponentially increase computing time and disk storage, be warned.
  • enzyme can take a bin size to directly bin aligned reads into fixed-width genomic windows, but filtering wonât work. This is generally non-advised.
  • I actually prefer to compute the P(s) (distance law) directly in R myself, from the pairs file. Weâll see how to do that later. In this case, you can skip --distance-law, for larger datasets this step takes a significant amount of time to compute.

5 Interact with a .pairs file

5.1 What is a .pairs file?

Each contact identified in Hi-C can be listed as a pair of 2 genomic locations.
For each pair of genomic loci making a contact, one comes from the *_R1 fastq file and the other comes from the *_R2 fastq file.
The .pairs format summarizes these contacts, and as such, it is the main, most important output of a Hi-C experiment. It is a human-readable, simplified version of a bam file generated from a paired-end sequencing. Information regarding sequencing/mapping quality, actual sequence, or other SAM flags, are discarded. The only remaining information are the genomic location of the end of each read.

The .pairs format has been formally defined as a tab-delimited text file containing 7 columns at least:

<read_id> <chrom1> <pos1> <chrom2> <pos2> <strand1> <strand2>
index name description
1 read_id the ID of the read as defined in fastq files
2 chrom1 the chromosome of the alignment on side 1
3 pos1 the 1-based genomic position of the outer-most (5â) mapped bp on side 1
4 chrom2 the chromosome of the alignment on side 2
5 pos2 the 1-based genomic position of the outer-most (5â) mapped bp on side 2
6 strand1 the strand of the alignment on side 1
7 strand2 the strand of the alignment on side 2

A number of .pairs files are present in results/tmp/.

bash
ls -ltFh results/tmp/*.pairs
-rw-rw-r-- 1 rsg rsg 615M 27 janv.  15:54 results/tmp/CH112.valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs
-rw-rw-r-- 1 rsg rsg 943M 27 janv.  15:50 results/tmp/CH112.valid_idx_filtered.pairs
-rw-rw-r-- 1 rsg rsg 1,2G 27 janv.  15:49 results/tmp/CH112.valid_idx.pairs
-rw-rw-r-- 1 rsg rsg 1,1G 27 janv.  15:45 results/tmp/CH112.valid.pairs

How many pairs are listed in each .pairs file?

bash
wc -l results/tmp/*.pairs

15809461 results/tmp/CH112.valid_idx.pairs
12557203 results/tmp/CH112.valid_idx_filtered.pairs
8090370 results/tmp/CH112.valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs

Few notes on which .pairs file to use
  • The *_pcrfree.pairs file is probably the one you want to use in your analyses. If you check the output of hicstuff, you can see that it is indeed generated after pairs filtering, so itâs ok to use it!
  • If you have a good reason to think that you may use pairs including PCR duplicates, go for the *_filtered.pairs file.
  • If you have a good reason to think that you may use unfiltered pairs including looping DNA fragments or uncut DNA fragments, go for the *.valid_idx.pairs file.
  • The remaining *.valid.pairs is redundant with the *.valid_idx.pairs and is probably not useful, it can be deleted.

A good practice is also to remove .bam files kept in the tmp/ folder.

Eventually, I recommend creating a new pairs/ folder, moving your .pairs files there, and deleting the remaining content of the tmp/ folder:

bash
mkdir results/pairs/
mv results/tmp/*valid_idx*.pairs results/pairs/
ls -ltFh results/pairs/
rm -rf results/tmp/

5.2 Check the QC plots for sanity controls

Several QC plots are generated by hicstuff, to assess the quality of pairs identified by HiC.

Understanding the event_distance plot

This plot illustrates how the nature of read pairs is inferred, based on the distance between the two reads (shown on the X axis) and their orientation. A pair of reads can have 4 different orientations: --, ++, -+ and +- (each + or - referring to the alignment on positive strand on negative strand of the DNA, i.e.Â directly on the genome reference or on its reverse complement).

  • -- and ++ pairs necessarily come from real religation events between two distant genomic loci (as long as there is at least > 0 restriction site between the two pairs). These pairs are unambiguously informative.
  • If there is no restriction site between reads of a --/++ pair, this pair is annotated as âweirdâ, as it should not exist.
  • +- and -+ pairs are ambiguous: they could either come from real religation events between two distant genomic loci (informative pairs) or from circular self-religated fragments (âloopsâ) or undigested fragments (âuncutsâ). hicstuff filters these ambiguous pairs by finding an appropriate threshold in minimum number of restriction fragments. +- and -+ pairs with less restriction fragments between their extremities are considered âuncutâ fragments and âself-religatedâ (âloopsâ) fragments and are discarded. The rest of the +- and -+ pairs are kept.

hicstuff generates a plot showing the distribution of these possible events:

  • -- and ++ informative pairs (in green)
  • -- and ++ weird pairs (with 0 restriction site between their extremities, in gray/dark)
  • -+ pairs: before the âloopsâ threshold, these pairs are annotated as âloopsâ; past this threshold, these pairs are considered informative.
  • +- pairs: before the âuncutâ threshold, these pairs are annotated as âuncutâ; past this threshold, these pairs are considered informative.
How hicstuff calculates the thresholds to estimate âloopsâ and âuncutsâ

Filtering consists in excluding +- and -+ pairs if their reads are closer than a threshold in minimum number of restriction fragments. This threshold represents the distance at which the abundance of these events stop deviating significantly from the rest of the library. It is estimated using the median absolute deviation of pairs.

More info here

Understanding the event_distribution plot

This pie chart represents the overall distribution of pairs for a Hi-C sample, as annotated by hicstuff.

  • Anything in purple (3D inter) or neon green (3D intra) comes is from informative, selected pairs. This is the value you want to be the highest! IME anything >50% is good. Lower than 20%, youâd have to question the quality of your biotin enrichmentâ¦
  • âWeirdsâ should be << 1%.
  • Loops and uncut will vary, according to their infered thresholds (explained in the previous subsection). The thresholds used to infer loops (uncut) fragments from -+ (+-) pairs are also printed in this plot.

Understanding the distance_law plot

The distance law is a good way to check that each of the chromosomes behaves as expected. In a yeast G1-synchronized sample, you expect a straight-ish line, with a slope of ~ -1.2 -> 1.5. In a yeast G2M-synchronized sample, you expect increased contacts in the 10-50kb range, visible as a âshoulderâ in the curve.

6 Creating a .cool contact matrix

6.1 What is a .cool file?

A .pairs is the most important file generated in a Hi-C pipeline, but itâs not the easiest one to use: it is huge, uncompressed, and unsummarized. In order to simplify the representation of Hi-C, pairs can be binned using a fixed-sized window (e.g.Â 1000 bp): every pair end falling in a 1kb bin will be assigned to this bin (same for the other end).

Eventually, one could transform this set of three (unambiguous informative) pairs:

CH112.valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs
<read_id> <chrom1> <pos1> <chrom2> <pos2> <strand1> <strand2>
NS500150:527:HHGYNBGXF:4:11503:19728:1057    I    32    I    1174    +    +
NS500150:527:HHGYNBGXF:1:22306:8892:6435     I    32    I    3725    +    +
NS500150:527:HHGYNBGXF:2:13311:15119:13685   I    78    I    3725    -    -

into a couple of files:

  1. A matrix file (effectively, a sparse matrix, which stores non-zero values in triplet format ijx):
matrix.mtx
<bin1> <bin2> <count>
1 2 1
1 4 2
COO (coordinate) sparse matrix structure

Note how only non-zero values are stored, efficiently reducing the disk storage footprint.

  1. A regions file:
regions.bed
<chr> <start> <end>
I    1       1000
I    1001    2000
I    2001    3000
I    3001    4000

A more sophisticated way to do this is to parse a pairs file with cooler. cooler does exactly what is shown above, but then compresses and indexes the information stored in a .cool file.

Eventually, the .cool (a variant of HDF5) format is just a sophisticated file structure to store rectangular matrices. Read more here.

6.2 Cooler

cooler library was written to perform several important operations:

  1. cload: parse .pairs files into .cool files
  2. balance: normalize Hi-C contact matrices (a.k.a âbalancingâ)
  3. dump: facilitate random access of a subset of the data using genomic coordinates
  4. show: enable visualization of Hi-C data
  5. zoomify: generate a multi-resolution .mcool file from a .cool file
bash
cooler --help
cooler cload --help
cooler balance --help
cooler dump --help
cooler show --help
cooler zoomify --help

6.2.1 cooler cload

Letâs first create a .cool file from a .pairs file. We can use any pairs file we want. In our case, since we want filtered and pcr-free pairs, we should use the *valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs file.

The generic command for cooler cloar is something like:

## GENERIC COMMAND: TO COMPLETE
## DO NOT RUN THIS!
cooler cload \
   pairs \
   --chrom1 ... --pos1 ... \ # chrom1 and pos1 column indices
   --chrom2 ... --pos2 ... \ # chrom2 and pos2 column indices
   <CHROMSIZES>:<BINSIZE> \ # path to chrom.sizes file followed by ":" then the desired bin size
   <PAIRS_PATH> \ # path to the input pairs file
   <COOL_PATH> # path to the output cool file

The CHROMSIZES should be a two-column text stream with chromosome names and lengths. One way to generate this is to use the `file generated byhicstuff`:

bash
sed 1d results/CH112.chr.tsv | cut -f1-2
I       230218
II      813184
III     316620
IV      1531933
V       576874
VI      270161
VII     1090940
VIII    562643
IX      439888
X       745751
XI      666816
XII     1078177
XIII    924431
XIV     784333
XV      1091291
XVI     948066
Mito    85779

We can execute cooler cload by âfeedingâ this text stream directly, using <(...) trick:

bash
mkdir results/matrix
cooler cload \
   pairs \
   --chrom1 2 --pos1 3 \
   --chrom2 4 --pos2 5 \
   <(sed 1d results/CH112.chr.tsv | cut -f1-2):1000 \
   results/pairs/CH112.valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs \
   results/matrix/CH112.cool

We can inspect the generated .cool file using cooler:

bash
cooler tree results/matrix/CH112.cool
cooler info results/matrix/CH112.cool
grep -v "#" results/pairs/CH112.valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs | wc -l
So what does hicstuff generate as a contact matrix??

You probably have noticed that hicstuff pipeline automatically creates a results/<PREFIX>.cool file. To understand the differences between results/<PREFIX>.cool and results/matrix/<PREFIX>.cool, one can use cooler info. Have a look at the "bin-size" and the "bin-type" keys printed in the terminal.

bash
cooler info results/CH112.cool
cooler info results/matrix/CH112.cool

The immediate output of hicstuff pipeline is a bin-less contact matrix! Each column/row actually represents a restriction fragment, rather than a fixed-width bin. The sum of contacts ("sum") is the same between the two files, but the number of bins (columns/rows) is different!

Here, we use cooler cload to convert a .pairs file into a .cool file. We could also have used hicstuff rebin, which uses a slightly different syntax to perform the same operation.

Filtering unwanted chromosomesâ¦

The <(...) trick illustrated above allows one to easily select/remove any chromosome they want to generate a chromosome-specific .cool file from a .pairs file:

bash
# --- Only select chromosome "II"
cooler cload \
   pairs \
   --chrom1 2 --pos1 3 \
   --chrom2 4 --pos2 5 \
   <(sed 1d results/CH112.chr.tsv | cut -f1-2 | grep -P "^II\t"):1000 \
   results/pairs/CH112.valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs \
   results/matrix/CH112_chrII.cool
cooler info results/matrix/CH112_chrII.cool

# --- Filter out "Mito" chromosome
cooler cload \
   pairs \
   --chrom1 2 --pos1 3 \
   --chrom2 4 --pos2 5 \
   <(sed 1d results/CH112.chr.tsv | cut -f1-2 | grep -Pv "^Mito\t"):1000 \
   results/pairs/CH112.valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs \
   results/matrix/CH112_noMito.cool
cooler info results/matrix/CH112_noMito.cool

6.2.2 cooler zoomify

One of the strength of .cool files is that they can be nested. In this case, one can generate a .mcool file, effectively containing several .cool files at different resolutions.

bash
cooler zoomify --help

We want to generate multi-resolution .mcool file for our Hi-C sample in order to study chromosome conformation at different scales, e.g.Â structural loops (~ tens of kb) to chromatin domains (~ hundreds of kb up to Mb).

At the same time, we will add normalized contact frequencies to each contact matrix. This can be done by using the --balance flag.

bash
cooler zoomify \
   --nproc 8 \
   --resolutions 1000,2000,4000,8000,16000 \
   --balance \
   --out results/matrix/CH112.mcool \
   results/matrix/CH112.cool

6.2.3 Recover contacts from a .cool file

A .mcool file is actually a nested list of .cool files!

bash
cooler tree results/matrix/CH112.mcool

Append ::/resolutions/<BINSIZE> to the end of .mcool file to access a specific resolution:

bash
cooler tree results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/16000
cooler info results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/16000

Raw contact counts (stored as a sparse matrix) along with the corresponding information regarding the genomic bins and the chromosomes can be recovered from a .cool file using cooler dump.

bash
cooler dump --help
cooler dump --header --table chroms results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/16000
cooler dump --header --table bins results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/16000 | head
cooler dump --header --table pixels --balanced results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/16000 | head
cooler dump --header --table pixels --balanced --join results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/16000 | head

One can access specific genomic locations using --range flag:

bash
cooler dump \
   --header \
   --table pixels \
   --balanced \
   --join \
   --range "I:48000-96000" \
   results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/16000

6.2.4 Imaging a contact matrix

The text format seen above is not very easy to parse, i.e.Â not very visually informative. Rather than dumping the .cool content as a text, we can use cooler to parse it into an image, a heatmap representing intensity of contacts between pairs of genomic loci.

bash
cooler show \
   --balanced \
   --out results/matrix/CH112_2kb-res_II-200kb-700kb.pdf \
   --dpi 500 \
   results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/2000 \
   II:200000-700000
Useful flags for cooler show
  • âbalanced If added, will plot the normalized contact matrix rather than the raw counts.
  • âzmin FLOAT The minimal value of the color scale.
  • âzmax FLOAT The maximal value of the color scale.
  • âcmap TEXT The colormap used to display the contact matrix (see the full list at http://matplotlib.org/examples/color/colormaps_reference.html
bash
cooler show \
   --balanced \
   --out results/matrix/CH112_2kb-res_II-200kb-700kb_-3to-1_inferno.pdf \
   --dpi 500 \
   --zmin='-3' \
   --zmax='-1' \
   --cmap="inferno" \
   results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/2000 \
   II:200000-700000

7 Using chromosight to map structural features

Mapping loops made easy, by Cyril Matthey-Doret!

bash
chromosight --help

Generic command:

bash
## GENERIC COMMAND: TO COMPLETE
## DO NOT RUN THIS!
chromosight detect \
   --pattern loops \
   --pearson <THRESHOLD> \
   --threads <@> \
   <contact_map> \
   <prefix>

In our case:

bash
mkdir results/loops/
chromosight detect \
   --pattern loops \
   --pearson 0.3 \
   --threads 4 \
   results/matrix/CH112.mcool::/resolutions/2000 \
   results/loops/CH112
bash
tree results/loops/
head results/loops/CH112.tsv

8 Recap: from reads to loops

bash
# ------ DEFINE ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
PREFIX=CH112
BINSIZE=1000
MULTIRES="1000,2000,4000,8000,16000"
THREADS=12
ENZYME="DpnII,HinfI"
GENOME="genomes/S288c/S288c.fa"

# ------ Prepare output folders
mkdir results/
mkdir results/matrix
mkdir results/loops
mkdir results/pairs

# ------ Fastq -> pairs
hicstuff pipeline \
   --distance-law \
   --duplicates \
   --enzyme "${ENZYME}" \
   --filter \
   --mapping normal \
   --matfmt cool \
   --no-cleanup \
   --outdir results \
   --plot \
   --prefix "${PREFIX}" \
   --threads "${THREADS}" \
   --genome "${GENOME}" \
   data/"${PREFIX}"_R1.fq.gz \
   data/"${PREFIX}"_R2.fq.gz

mv results/tmp/*valid_idx*.pairs results/pairs/

# ------ pairs -> cool
cooler cload \
   pairs \
   --chrom1 2 --pos1 3 \
   --chrom2 4 --pos2 5 \
   <(sed 1d results/"${PREFIX}".chr.tsv | cut -f1-2):"${BINSIZE}" \
   results/pairs/"${PREFIX}".valid_idx_pcrfree.pairs \
   results/matrix/"${PREFIX}".cool

# ------ cool -> mcool
cooler zoomify \
   --nproc "${THREADS}" \
   --resolutions "${MULTIRES}" \
   --balance \
   --out results/matrix/"${PREFIX}".mcool \
   results/matrix/"${PREFIX}".cool

# ------ cool -> loops
chromosight detect \
   --pattern loops \
   --threads "${THREADS}" \
   results/matrix/"${PREFIX}".mcool::/resolutions/"${BINSIZE}" \
   results/loops/"${PREFIX}"

9 Going further: cooltools

Several advanced features are available with cooltools, notably:

  1. Finding âdotsâ: i.e.Â finding loops in a contact map
  2. Computing eigenvectors: i.e.Â annotating compartments in a contact map (usually @ coarse resolution)
  3. Computing insulation: i.e.Â annotating topological domains in a contact map (usually @ finer resolution)
  4. Computing pileup: a.k.a Aggregated Plot Analysis (APA)
  5. Computing saddle plots

10 Going even further: HiCExperiment ecosystem in R

  • HiCExperiment:

    • Import and subset contact matrices (.cool, .hic, HiC-Pro derivedâ¦)
    • Import and subset pairs files

  • HiContacts:

    • Arithmetics: merge, divide, smoothen, balance, autocorrelate, â¦
    • Analysis: P(s), virtual 4C, scalograms, cis/trans interactions
    • Mapping: chromatin loops (via chromosight), topological domains, compartments
    • Visualizing: contact maps, features, aggregated maps, saddle plots

  • HiCool:

    • Runs hicstuff+cooler embarked in R
    • Generates multi-resolution, balanced .mcool files from read pairs
    • Computes automated reports

  • fourDNData:

    • Gateway to the 4DN consortium data portal

11 Extra: Integrating HiC with other genome-wide modalities

bash
mamba install -c bioconda \
   bioconductor-rtracklayer \
   bioconductor-plyranges \
   r-ggplot2 \
   r-tidyr
R
library(ggplot2)
library(rtracklayer)
library(plyranges)

# - Import gene annotations as GenomicRanges
genes <- import('genomes/S288c/S288c.gtf') |> 
   filter(type == 'gene')

# - Import tracks as Run-length vectors
scc1 <- import('tracks/CH224.CPM.bw', as = 'Rle')
rnaseq_fwd <- import('tracks/SRR2045244.fwd.CPM.bw', as = 'Rle')
rnaseq_rev <- import('tracks/SRR2045244.rev.CPM.bw', as = 'Rle')

# - Define locus of interest
locus <- GRanges("II:300000-350000")
bins <- tile(locus, width = 10)[[1]]

# - Average tracks over bins
df <- data.frame(
   pos = start(bins), 
   scc1 = mean(scc1[bins]), 
   rnaseq_fwd = mean(rnaseq_fwd[bins]), 
   rnaseq_rev = -mean(rnaseq_rev[bins])  
) |> 
   tidyr::pivot_longer(-pos, names_to = 'track', values_to = 'score') |> 
   dplyr::mutate(track = factor(track, c('scc1', 'rnaseq_fwd', 'rnaseq_rev')))

# - Plot tracks 
p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = pos, y = score, fill = track)) + 
   geom_area(position = 'identity', alpha = 0.5) + 
   scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) + 
   theme_bw() + 
   theme(legend.position = 'bottom')
ggsave('results/plots/tracks.pdf', width = 10, height = 4)

# - Plot faceted tracks 
p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = pos, y = score, fill = track)) + 
   geom_area(position = 'identity') + 
   scale_x_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) + 
   theme_bw() + 
   theme(legend.position = 'bottom') + 
   facet_grid(track~., scales = 'free')
ggsave('results/plots/tracks_facets.pdf', width = 10, height = 7)
